Certainly! Here's a simple example of a search function in JavaScript that searches through an array of items based on user input:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8" />
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
<title>Simple Search Function</title>
</head>
<body>

<input type="text" id="searchInput" placeholder="Search..." />
<button onclick="search()">Search</button>

<ul id="results"></ul>

<script>
  // Sample data array
  const data = [
    'Apple',
    'Banana',
    'Cherry',
    'Date',
    'Elderberry',
    'Fig',
    'Grape',
  ];

  function search() {
    const input = document.getElementById('searchInput').value.toLowerCase();
    const results = document.getElementById('results');

    // Clear previous results
    results.innerHTML = '';

    // Filter data based on input
    const filteredData = data.filter(item => item.toLowerCase().includes(input));

    // Display results
    if (filteredData.length === 0) {
      results.innerHTML = '<li>No results found</li>';
    } else {
      filteredData.forEach(item => {
        const li = document.createElement('li');
        li.textContent = item;
        results.appendChild(li);
      });
    }
  }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How it works:
- You enter a search term in the input box.
- When you click the "Search" button, the `search()` function runs.
- It filters the `data` array, matching items that contain the search term (case-insensitive).
- The matching items are displayed as a list below the input box.
- If no matches are found, it displays "No results found".

Feel free to customize the data array or the UI as needed!
